==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pedant
<hw>Ped"ant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>p⟦eacute⟧dant</ets>, It. <ets>pedante</ets>, fr. Gr.
<grk>paidey`ein</grk> to instruct, from <grk>pai^s</grk> boy. See
<er>Pedagogue</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A schoolmaster; a
pedagogue.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>pedant</qex> that keeps a school i'th' church.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>One who puts on an air of learning; one who makes a
vain display of learning; a pretender to superior knowledge.</def>
<rj><au>Addison.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A scholar, yet surely no <qex>pedant</qex>, was he.</q>
<rj><qau>Goldsmith.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pedantical</ent>⟦br⟧
<ent>Pedantic</ent>⟦br⟧
